    "message_1": "A certain type of traffic accident has a probability of 0.05 of occurring on a certain road each day. If there are 100,000 vehicles that travel on that road per day, what is the probability that at least 50 of them will experience this type of accident in one day?",
    "message_2": "To solve this problem, we can use the binomial probability formula, which is:\n\nP(X = k) = C(n, k) * p^k * (1-p)^(n-k)\n\nwhere:\n- P(X = k) is the probability of exactly k successes (accidents) in n trials (vehicles)\n- C(n, k) is the number of combinations of n items taken k at a time, also written as n! / (k!(n-k)!)\n- p is the probability of a single success (accident)\n- n is the number of trials (vehicles)\n- k is the number of successes (accidents)\n\nIn this case, we want to find the probability of at least 50 accidents, which means we need to find the sum of probabilities for 50, 51, 52, ..., 100,000 accidents. Mathematically, this can be represented as:\n\nP(X >= 50) = 1 - P(X < 50) = 1 - Σ P(X = k) for k = 0 to 49\n\nwhere:\n- P(X >= 50) is the probability of at least 50 accidents\n- P(X < 50) is the probability of fewer than 50 accidents\n\nNow, we can plug in the values given in the problem:\n\nn = 100,000 (number of vehicles)\np = 0.05 (probability of an accident)\n\nWe can calculate P(X < 50) by summing the probabilities for k = 0 to 49:\n\nP(X < 50) = Σ P(X = k) for k = 0 to 49\n\nThis calculation involves a large number of terms and can be computationally intensive. It's more practical to use statistical software or a calculator with a built-in binomial cumulative distribution function (CDF) to find the sum.\n\nUsing a calculator or software, we find:\n\nP(X < 50) ≈ 0."
